<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900712-0033</DOCNO><DOCID>900712-0033.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Publisher Lang to Launch   TV Network Airing Reruns</HL><DATE>07/12/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK (AP) -- Magazine publisher Dale Lang said heplans to launch a television network this fall that willfeature direct-response advertising programs and reruns ofclassic television shows.   Mr. Lang, chairman of the newly created Star TelevisionNetwork Inc., said 23 independent UHF stations -- reachingmore than 13.7 million of the nation's 92 million TV-owninghouseholds -- have agreed to carry the service starting inSeptember.</LP><TEXT>   Stations that sign affiliation agreements will be giveneight hours of television programs a day, consisting ofmovies, game shows and series like &quot;Life of Riley,&quot; &quot;TheInvaders&quot; and &quot;Richard Diamond,&quot; Mr. Lang said.   In exchange for the programs, the stations must run atleast four hours a day of direct-response programs, alsocalled &quot;infomercials.&quot; These are program-length commercialsin which a marketer typically demonstrates a product andinvites viewers to call in to order.   Mr. Lang said Star Television and the producers of theinfomercials would share revenue from sales of the productsor services with affiliate stations.   A spokeswoman for Mr. Lang couldn't say how much was beinginvested in the new network. The network will be transmittedto member stations via satellite.   Mr. Lang also heads Lang Communications, a New York-basedmedia company that publishes Working Woman, Working Mother,Sassy and Success magazines.</TEXT></DOC>